{% block content %}
<article class="anm-wrap">

  <p class="anm-num">OIATC · Project · Language</p>
  <h1>Anishinaabemowin</h1>
  <p class="anm-lede">A working project. This page is its public home and grows as the work does.</p>
  <p class="anm-updated">Last updated: June 12, 2026.</p>

  <nav class="anm-jump" aria-label="On this page">
    <a href="#numbers">01 · The numbers</a>
    <a href="#built">02 · Built and running</a>
    <a href="#streams">03 · The four streams</a>
    <a href="#waaseyaa">04 · Built on Waaseyaa</a>
    <a href="#settled">05 · Settled and deciding</a>
    <a href="#log">06 · Progress log</a>
    <a href="#take-part">07 · Take part</a>
    <a href="#sources">08 · Sources</a>
  </nav>

  <div class="anm-col" style="margin-top: var(--gap-6)">
    <p>This is a live, community-owned project to keep Anishinaabemowin alive through the next twenty years: record fluent speakers, build low-pressure places to hear and use the language, and ship learning tools on technology the community controls. It is led by Russell Jones in Sagamok Anishnawbek. Working apps are already running. This page tracks what exists, what is being built, and how to take part.</p>
  </div>

  <section class="anm-sec" id="numbers">
    <div class="anm-sec__head"><span class="anm-num">01</span><h2>The numbers, plainly</h2></div>
    <div class="anm-stats">
      <div class="anm-stat"><b>26,165</b><span>people in Canada who can hold a conversation in an Ojibway language (2021 Census)</span></div>
      <div class="anm-stat"><b>48</b><span>average age of the mother-tongue population, second oldest among major Algonquian languages</span></div>
      <div class="anm-stat"><b>1 in 5</b><span>Ojibway speakers who use the language most often at home, the lowest such share</span></div>
      <div class="anm-stat"><b>~1,000</b><span>estimated fluent Ojibwe speakers in the United States, most of them Elders</span></div>
    </div>
    <div class="anm-col" style="margin-top: var(--gap-5)">
      <p>The 2021 Census counted 26,165 people in Canada who can hold a conversation in an Ojibway language, and 15,890 who have it as their mother tongue. The average age of that mother-tongue population is 48, the second oldest among the major Algonquian languages. Nearly half of today's speakers (47.5 percent) learned the language as a second language, the clearest sign that first-language transmission has thinned and learners are carrying more of the load.</p>
      <p>Use at home is the weakest link. Only about one in five Ojibway speakers uses the language most often at home, the lowest share among the large Algonquian languages. In Ontario, the number of First Nations people speaking Ojibway languages fell 8.7 percent between 2016 and 2021, and people 65 and older are more than twice as likely to speak an Indigenous language as children 14 and under. South of the border, estimates put fluent Ojibwe speakers in the United States at roughly a thousand, most of them Elders.</p>
      <p>The first-language generation is in its fifties, sixties, and seventies now. The next twenty years decide whether transmission restarts or ends. Nobody, on either side of the border, has an actual count of fluent speakers by name and community. That is the gap this project works inside.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <p class="anm-pull">The next twenty years decide whether transmission restarts or ends.</p>

  <section class="anm-sec" id="built">
    <div class="anm-sec__head"><span class="anm-num">02</span><h2>What's built and running</h2></div>
    <p class="anm-col">This is not a plan waiting for funding. These exist today.</p>
    <div class="anm-cards">
      <div class="anm-card anm-card--live">
        <h3>The corpus pipeline <span class="anm-badge">running</span></h3>
        <p>Tooling that takes a fluent speaker's recordings and produces curated, consent-tracked corpus items: audio, transcription, provenance. The first corpus, drawn from one Elder's public teaching videos and used with his agreement, has 27 curated items from roughly 50 source videos.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anm-card anm-card--live">
        <h3>The lesson app <span class="anm-badge">running</span></h3>
        <p>Lesson 1 (kitchen vocabulary, 16 items) runs as a browser app: cards with image, audio, Anishinaabemowin, and English, with a practice mode that hides the English, plus a shareable preview built for Elder review.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anm-card anm-card--live">
        <h3>Transcription and translation helpers <span class="anm-badge">running</span></h3>
        <p>A local web tool for moving recordings into the corpus by hand: audio playback beside paired Anishinaabemowin and English fields, so a human, not a model, decides what the record says. Machine drafts are allowed as suggestions and never treated as truth.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anm-card anm-card--live">
        <h3>Learning games on Minoo <span class="anm-badge">live</span></h3>
        <p>A suite of Anishinaabemowin games is live at <a href="https://minoo.live" target="_blank" rel="noopener">minoo.live</a>, built on the platform's dictionary data: <a href="https://minoo.live/games/shkoda" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Shkoda</a> (word guessing around a campfire), <a href="https://minoo.live/games/matcher" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Matcher</a> (word-pair matching), <a href="https://minoo.live/games/agim" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Agim</a> (numbers), a <a href="https://minoo.live/games/crossword" target="_blank" rel="noopener">crossword</a>, and Minoo's Journey (find-the-word scenes). Daily challenges, practice modes, and player stats. They are the proof that the data model carries real apps, not just records.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="anm-sec" id="streams">
    <div class="anm-sec__head"><span class="anm-num">03</span><h2>The four streams</h2></div>
    <p class="anm-col">One principle across everything: the technology serves the relationships, not the other way around.</p>
    <div class="anm-cards">
      <div class="anm-card">
        <h3><span class="anm-badge">1</span> Record fluent speakers now</h3>
        <p>Extend the corpus pipeline beyond one Elder into a repeatable record-curate-consent workflow, and build a speaker registry: who the fluent speakers are, where, and what dialect, starting with Sagamok and the North Shore, designed so any community can run its own count.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anm-card">
        <h3><span class="anm-badge">2</span> Build places to hear the language</h3>
        <p>Most revitalization work fails on format, not demand. The answer here is listening-first: nbwaachewin (visiting) evenings where fluent speakers tell stories and learners listen, no curriculum, no performance pressure, plus standing open online sessions. The generation that grew up hearing the language but does not speak it readily is the first audience.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anm-card">
        <h3><span class="anm-badge">3</span> Ship the structured course</h3>
        <p>One shared core (language data, spaced repetition, audio, consent tracking) serving three audiences: adult community members, youth classrooms, and self-directed remote learners. Twelve-month target: one complete unit, eight to twelve lessons, end to end.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anm-card">
        <h3><span class="anm-badge">4</span> Keep the core open and the content gated</h3>
        <p>The code is open source; another Nation can fork the system and put their own language behind it. The language content is community-controlled and never ships with the code. Nothing enters the corpus without a human pass, no AI ever generates Anishinaabemowin for the corpus, and spelling stays exactly as the speaker writes it.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="anm-sec" id="waaseyaa">
    <div class="anm-sec__head"><span class="anm-num">04</span><h2>Built on Waaseyaa</h2></div>
    <div class="anm-col">
      <p>The project runs on <a href="https://waaseyaa.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener" style="color: var(--accent-deep)">Waaseyaa</a>, the framework OIATC stewards, where governance is structural rather than bolted on. The capabilities that matter for language work:</p>
    </div>
    <ul class="anm-list">
      <li><strong>Translatable, revisionable entities.</strong> Every record can carry Anishinaabemowin and English as live versions of the same entity, down to the individual field, with full revision history.</li>
      <li><strong>Structural access control with an audit trail.</strong> Per-entity and per-field access policies, and an append-only log of every access and change. Consent is data, not a checkbox: each item records what uses it is approved for.</li>
      <li><strong>An ingestion pipeline with editorial gates.</strong> Recordings and metadata flow in through adapters, get chunked and validated, and wait at a human quality gate before anything publishes.</li>
      <li><strong>AI grounded on approved content only.</strong> Chat and search run against the community-approved corpus and dictionary through retrieval, with keys server-side. The model never invents language content.</li>
      <li><strong>Multi-tenant by design.</strong> One installation can serve many Nations as separate groups with isolated content and their own policies.</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="anm-col" style="margin-top: var(--gap-4)">
      <p><a href="https://minoo.live" target="_blank" rel="noopener" style="color: var(--accent-deep)">Minoo</a>, the first platform built on Waaseyaa, adds the language domain itself: dictionary entries, example sentences, word parts, speakers, and dialect regions, plus the game engines that run on top of them. That is where this project's data lives long-term.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="anm-sec" id="settled">
    <div class="anm-sec__head"><span class="anm-num">05</span><h2>What is settled, what is being decided</h2></div>
    <div class="anm-twocol">
      <div class="anm-panel">
        <h3>Settled</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>the Elder-first ground rules</li>
          <li>the shared-core, three-shells architecture</li>
          <li>the first corpus source</li>
          <li>the open-code, gated-content license posture</li>
          <li>Waaseyaa and Minoo as the platform layer</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="anm-panel">
        <h3>Being decided</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>the written consent record format that scales past a trusted-collaborator phase</li>
          <li>the speaker registry design</li>
          <li>the format and cadence of the first community listening sessions</li>
          <li>which community partners carry the youth classroom shell</li>
          <li>how the Minoo games and the corpus-based course converge on one data spine</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="anm-sec" id="log">
    <div class="anm-sec__head"><span class="anm-num">06</span><h2>Progress log</h2></div>
    <div class="anm-log">
      <!-- Newest first. To append, copy one .anm-log__entry block and place it at
           the top: a date in .anm-log__date and a short paragraph in .anm-log__body. -->
      <div class="anm-log__entry">
        <div class="anm-log__date">2026-06-12</div>
        <div class="anm-log__body">This project section published. Program plan written, unifying the corpus work, community sessions, course, platform, and the Minoo apps into one program with a 90-day and 12-month roadmap.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="anm-log__entry">
        <div class="anm-log__date">2026-05-14 to late May</div>
        <div class="anm-log__body">First corpus built: 27 curated items from roughly 50 public teaching videos. Lesson 1 (kitchen vocabulary, 16 items) shipped as a browser app with a shareable preview for Elder review. Transcription helper built. Five decision records adopted.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="anm-log__entry">
        <div class="anm-log__date">2026-05-14</div>
        <div class="anm-log__body">Project started as parallel R&amp;D alongside Sagamok's accreditation track.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="anm-log__entry">
        <div class="anm-log__date">Earlier, on Minoo</div>
        <div class="anm-log__body">The language game suite (Shkoda, Matcher, Agim, crossword, Journey) shipped on minoo.live with daily challenges and player stats.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="anm-sec" id="take-part">
    <div class="anm-sec__head"><span class="anm-num">07</span><h2>Take part</h2></div>
    <div class="anm-cta">
      <p>The project is looking for fluent speakers and Elders who want their voice recorded on their own terms, semi-speakers who want somewhere to listen, teachers, researchers who can put rigor behind the speaker count, and developers for the open core.</p>
      <a class="anm-cta__btn" href="mailto:jonesrussell42@gmail.com">Email Russell &rarr;</a>
      <span class="anm-cta__addr">Write to Russell: <a href="mailto:jonesrussell42@gmail.com">jonesrussell42@gmail.com</a></span>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="anm-sec" id="sources">
    <div class="anm-sec__head"><span class="anm-num">08</span><h2>Sources</h2></div>
    <ul class="anm-sources">
      <li>Statistics Canada and the Office of the Commissioner of Indigenous Languages, "Indigenous Language Families: Algonquian languages," 2021 Census thematic report (March 2025): <a href="https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/pub/41-20-0002/412000022025002-eng.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/pub/41-20-0002/412000022025002-eng.htm</a></li>
      <li>Statistics Canada, "Indigenous languages across Canada," Census in Brief: <a href="https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2021/as-sa/98-200-x/2021012/98-200-x2021012-eng.cfm" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2021/as-sa/98-200-x/2021012/98-200-x2021012-eng.cfm</a></li>
      <li>Statistics Canada, The Daily, "Indigenous language families in Canada" (March 31, 2025): <a href="https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/daily-quotidien/250331/dq250331a-eng.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/daily-quotidien/250331/dq250331a-eng.htm</a></li>
      <li>University of Minnesota, Ojibwe People's Dictionary, on US fluent-speaker estimates: <a href="https://ojibwe.lib.umn.edu/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://ojibwe.lib.umn.edu/</a></li>
      <li>CBC News on 2021 census data gaps for Indigenous languages: <a href="https://www.cbc.ca/news/indigenous/indigenous-languages-2021-census-data-1.6554041" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www.cbc.ca/news/indigenous/indigenous-languages-2021-census-data-1.6554041</a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <p class="anm-byline">Russell Jones, on behalf of OIATC. Independent of the bodies named. Corrections welcome.</p>

</article>
